      "content": "The expansion of the social safety net has indeed contributed to a decline in labor participation rates over the last decade. Increased benefits and stronger safety nets can create disincentives for job-seeking, as individuals may feel more secure without the need to work. This effect can be particularly pronounced in welfare programs that provide substantial income without requiring employment. While the intention of such programs is to support those in need, they can inadvertently reduce the motivation to seek employment, leading to lower labor participation rates.",
